<sect>Installation<p>

<sect1>How to obtain kvoctrain<p>  

Major releases of
<tt/kvoctrain/ can be found on the <tt/KDE/ server at the appropriate place in
<htmlurl url="ftp://ftp.kde.org/pub/kde/unstable/apps/education/"
        name="ftp.kde.org/pub/kde/unstable/apps/education/">.

Current snapshots, dictionary files  and tools needed to make modifications
can be found on the 
<htmlurl url="http://kvoctrain.sourceforge.net/download/download.html"
        name="kvoctrain homepage">.

<htmlurl url="http://sourceforge.net/cvs/?group_id=9265"
        name="Anonymous CVS download"> is also available.

You can find precompiled binaries as rpm packages for the SuSE distribution
(of almost all KDE apps):
<htmlurl url="http://www.suse.de/download/LinuKS/"
         name="LinuKS: SuSE Linux KDE Service">.

Another place for precompiled packages is 
<htmlurl url="http://xmission.linuxberg.com/kdehtml/ent_educational.html#kvoctrain"
         name="Linuxberg">.



<sect1>Requirements<p>

In order to successfully compile <tt/kvoctrain/, you need the
<tt/KDE/ libraries as well as the <tt/Qt/ C++ library. All required libraries
can be found on
<htmlurl url="ftp://ftp.kde.org/pub/kde/"
        name="ftp.kde.org/pub/kde/">.

<tt/kvoctrain/ is tested with <tt/KDE 1.1.2/ and <tt/Qt 1.44/ as well
as <tt/KDE 2.0/ and <tt/QT 2.2.3/.

<sect1>Compilation and installation<p>

In order to compile and install <tt/kvoctrain/ on your system, type the following in
the base directory of the <tt/kvoctrain/ distribution:

<tscreen><verb>
% ./configure
% make
% su
% make install    
% make distclean
</verb></tscreen>

<p>
Since <tt/kvoctrain/ uses <tt/autoconf/ you should have not trouble
compiling it.
Should you run into problems please report them to the the author
<htmlurl url="mailto:ewald at ewald-arnold.de" name = "ewald at ewald-arnold.de">

<sect>Working with kvoctrain<p>

<sect1>Overview<p>

As you can see below, the entries of the vocabulary are arranged similar to
a spreadsheet.
Each column represents an expression or word in one language. The leftmost
column contains the name of the lesson this entry belongs to.
The second is always the original word and the others to the right of it
represent the respective translations.


<figure>
  <eps file="mainview.eps">
  <IMG
   BORDER="0"
   WIDTH="725"
   HEIGHT="436"
   SRC="mainview.png"
   ALT="[main view]">
</figure>


In the picture above, you can also see that several properties of the
vocabulary have a visual representation:

 <itemize>
  <item>colors show the grade (Level 1 to 7) of your knowledge

  <item>bold face lines are currently selected for a query

  <item>if you mark a range of entries to work with, they appear with a
        different background.
 </itemize>

The color in the column with the original will vary if you have two columns
with translations. If the cursor is in one of the translations the color
represents its grade "to the original". See section
<htmlurl url="#entry2-dlg" name="entry dialog"> for more on this.

Of course it is also possible to use it as an ordinary dictionary and
<htmlurl url="#smart-search"  name="lookup manually">.

On the bottom of the main window you also see the status line which usually
contains the three areas that show properties of the current expression if
available:

 <itemize>
   <item>T: the <htmlurl name="type" url="#types"> of this word
   <item>P: how to pronunce this expression
   <item>R: your personal remarks
 </itemize>
   
<p>
While <tt/kvoctrain/ is loading, saving a large file or otherwise busy doing something
time consuming, you will see a progress bar in this status line.

