     for me to play around and test some things.
     <p>
     <bf>
     No version of <tt/kvoctrain/ will ever be able to read binary files
     from previous or later versions! This (mis-)behaviour is intended!
     </bf>
     <p>
-->
   <item>
     Vocabulary files from
     <htmlurl name="vocabbox"
              url="http://www.kiecza.de/daniel/linux/">
     which is the leanest vocabulary trainer I know. I recommend this
     application if you need a really compact one.
     <p>

   <item>
     Files created by
     <htmlurl name="Vocabulary Trainer"
               url="http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/michael_m_werner/">.  This is an application
     for M$ Windoze. It uses the file extension "lex". Link seems to be dead.

     See the section about
     <htmlurl url="index-4.html#dictionary"
             name="available dictionaries">
     to download these files.
     <p>
     
   <item>
     Simple text files with special delimiters between the entries which are
     also used by simpled database programs. The extension is "csv" in this
     case.

     There are a lot of dictionaries on the internet which use the tabular
     character or one or two colons to separate the different languages.

     To select this separator use the dialog for setting the 
     <htmlurl url="#options2-dlg"
              name="clipboard options">.
     <p>
 </itemize>

<tt/kvoctrain/ reads the first few bytes from a file and makes a guess
about the file format. When none of the special types like kvtml or lex
are recognized, it uses the csv format.

